VALUES
(42, 13, 26, 23, 58, 2, 2, 'taught in our streets', 'Seeking God and His Ways', 'This connection highlights the theme of seeking God and His teachings. Both passages emphasize the desire to know God''s ways and the experience of being in His presence.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 26, 56, 1, 16, 16, 'We have eaten and drunk in thy presence', 'Connection of Knowledge and Action', 'This connection highlights the contrast between professing knowledge of God and the lack of corresponding actions. Both passages emphasize that mere association with Christ does not equate to true obedience or faithfulness.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 26, 55, 3, 5, 5, 'We have eaten and drunk in thy presence', 'Connection of False Assurance', 'This connection highlights the theme of false assurance in faith. Both passages emphasize the idea of individuals claiming familiarity with God while lacking true spiritual power or authenticity.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 27, 19, 6, 8, 8, 'depart from me, all ye workers of iniquity', 'Connection of Iniquity Workers', 'Both passages emphasize the phrase ''depart from me, all ye workers of iniquity,'' highlighting a rejection of those who commit wrongdoing. This connection underscores a theme of divine judgment against iniquity.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 27, 40, 25, 41, 41, 'Depart from me, all ye workers of iniquity.', 'Connection of Departing from Judgment', 'Both passages emphasize the act of departing from the presence of the Lord as a consequence for wrongdoing. They highlight the rejection of those identified as ''workers of iniquity'' or ''cursed'', indicating a similar theme of judgment and separation.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 27, 19, 119, 115, 115, 'depart from me, all ye workers of iniquity', 'Connection of Evildoers and Commandments', 'Both passages emphasize the rejection of evildoers. The phrase ''depart from me'' in both verses highlights a similar theme of separation from those who do iniquity.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 27, 40, 7, 22, 23, 'depart from me, all ye workers of iniquity', 'Rejection of Workers of Iniquity', 'Both passages emphasize the rejection of those who claim to serve God but are identified as workers of iniquity. They highlight the disconnect between outward actions and true recognition by Christ.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 27, 28, 9, 12, 12, 'depart from me, all ye workers of iniquity', 'Divine Rejection and Bereavement', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine rejection and the consequences of iniquity. Both passages emphasize a separation from God, where those identified as workers of iniquity are told to depart, paralleling the bereavement expressed in Hosea.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 27, 42, 13, 25, 25, 'I know you not whence ye are', 'Connection of Rejection by the Master', 'Both passages emphasize the master''s rejection of those who claim to know him. The phrase ''I know you not whence ye are'' appears in both, highlighting the theme of exclusion for workers of iniquity.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 27, 55, 2, 19, 19, NULL, 'Connection of Iniquity and Knowledge', 'Both passages emphasize the relationship between knowing God and departing from iniquity. In Luke, those who are workers of iniquity are rejected, while in 2 Timothy, the Lord knows those who are His and calls them to depart from iniquity.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 28, 40, 8, 11, 12, 'there shall be weeping and gnashing of teeth', 'Weeping and Gnashing of Teeth', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of exclusion from the kingdom of God, highlighting the sorrow of those who are cast out. The mention of ''weeping and gnashing of teeth'' in both verses underscores the severity of this judgment.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 28, 40, 22, 13, 13, 'weeping and gnashing of teeth', 'Weeping and Gnashing of Teeth', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of punishment and exclusion from the kingdom of God, highlighting the intense sorrow associated with being cast out. The phrase ''weeping and gnashing of teeth'' appears in both, underscoring the severity of the consequences for those rejected.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 28, 66, 21, 8, 8, 'weeping and gnashing of teeth', 'Consequences of Exclusion', 'Both passages emphasize the dire consequences for those excluded from God''s kingdom. Luke 13:28 speaks of ''weeping and gnashing of teeth,'' while Revelation 21:8 describes the fate of the ''fearful'' and ''unbelieving'' in the lake of fire.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 28, 19, 112, 10, 10, 'gnashing of teeth', 'Weeping and Gnashing of Teeth', 'This connection highlights the theme of grief and despair experienced by the wicked. Both passages emphasize ''gnashing of teeth'' as a response to exclusion from the blessings of God''s kingdom.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 28, 42, 10, 15, 15, 'thrust out', 'Judgment and Exclusion Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of judgment and exclusion from the kingdom of God. In Luke 13:28, those who are ''thrust out'' are contrasted with the patriarchs in the kingdom, while Luke 10:15 speaks of Capernaum being ''thrust down to hell.''', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 28, 42, 14, 15, 15, 'kingdom of God', 'Kingdom of God Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of the kingdom of God. The first passage warns of exclusion from this kingdom, while the second passage expresses a blessing for those who will partake in it.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 28, 53, 1, 5, 5, 'kingdom of God', 'Judgment and Worthiness Themes', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of being counted worthy of the kingdom of God. Luke 13:28 warns of exclusion from the kingdom, while 2 Thessalonians 1:5 speaks of suffering to be deemed worthy. This connection highlights the serious implications of one''s standing before God.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 29, 23, 43, 6, 6, 'north, and from the south', 'Gathering from All Directions', 'Both passages emphasize the gathering of people from various directions, indicating a universal call to God''s kingdom. The mention of ''north'' and ''south'' in both verses highlights this theme of inclusivity.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 29, 23, 49, 6, 6, 'from the east, and from the west', 'Inclusivity of God''s Kingdom', 'This connection highlights the theme of God''s salvation extending beyond Israel to all nations. Both passages emphasize the gathering of people from various directions, indicating a universal invitation to the kingdom of God.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 29, 39, 1, 11, 11, 'shall come from the east, and from the west, and from the north, and from the south', 'Gentiles in God''s Kingdom', 'This connection highlights the inclusion of Gentiles in God''s kingdom. Both passages emphasize that people from various directions will honor God, indicating a universal scope of worship.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 29, 1, 28, 14, 14, 'from the east, and from the west, and from the north, and from the south', 'Connection of Geographic Blessings', 'Both passages emphasize the directions of east, west, north, and south, highlighting a universal scope of God''s kingdom and blessings. This connection illustrates the inclusivity of God''s promise to all families of the earth.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 29, 44, 28, 28, 28, 'kingdom of God', 'Salvation for All Nations', 'This connection highlights the inclusivity of God''s kingdom, as both passages emphasize that people from various directions will come to God. Luke 13:29 speaks of individuals coming from all directions to sit in the kingdom, while Acts 28:28 indicates that salvation is extended to the Gentiles, who will hear it.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 29, 49, 3, 6, 8, 'kingdom of God', 'Inclusion of Gentiles in God''s Kingdom', 'This connection highlights the theme of inclusivity in God''s kingdom. Both passages emphasize that people from various backgrounds, including Gentiles, will be partakers of God''s promise and sit in the kingdom.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 29, 66, 7, 9, 10, 'from the east, and from the west, and from the north, and from the south', 'Gathering of Nations', 'This connection highlights the gathering of people from diverse backgrounds in the kingdom of God. Both passages emphasize a multitude from various nations and directions coming together to worship.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 30, 40, 19, 30, 30, NULL, 'First and Last Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the reversal of status, where those who are first will become last and vice versa. This thematic connection highlights the idea of humility and the unexpected nature of God''s kingdom.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 30, 40, 20, 16, 16, 'last which shall be first', 'Last and First Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the reversal of status, where the last become first and the first become last. This connection highlights a shared theme of divine justice and the unexpected nature of God''s kingdom.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 30, 40, 21, 28, 31, 'last which shall be first', 'Last and First Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the reversal of expectations regarding who will enter the kingdom of God. In Luke, the ''last'' becoming ''first'' parallels the first son who ultimately obeys the father''s will, contrasting with the second son who does not.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 30, 41, 10, 31, 31, NULL, 'First and Last Concept', 'Both passages emphasize the reversal of status, where those who are first will be last and vice versa. This thematic connection highlights the idea of unexpected outcomes in the kingdom of God.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 30, 40, 3, 9, 10, 'last which shall be first', 'Reversal of Status Theme', 'Both passages emphasize a reversal of status, where those presumed to be first may end up last. In Luke, the last shall be first, while Matthew warns that those relying on their heritage without good fruit will face judgment.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 13, 31, 16, 6, 9, 11, NULL, 'Fear of Threatened Violence', 'This connection highlights the theme of fear in both passages, where individuals are warned of impending danger. In Luke, the Pharisees warn Jesus of Herod''s intent to kill him, while in Nehemiah, there is a warning of an assassination plot against him. Both emphasize the response to threats of violence.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
